story: My first sticky note! It's a canyon. I remeber being dissatisfied with the drawing at the time, but now I don't think it's so bad.
This is the day I had my first pomelo.
I had a holk hogan mustache for about two months somewhere in here. I grew it as a gag for Corbin's birthday ski trip, but it stuck around for two months.
This is our living room in 178 parker ave. Maybe this is what God sees while following me around all the time.
At this point I said, "enough with this beige background" and got to the real deal -- white stickies.
I broke up with someone on this day. No one felt good about it.
I traced a bunch of different coins for this. They look like space fireballs.
I'm not too happy with the drawing on this one, but I really like the idea and the line "Thou shalt not snitch"
I'm still not even sure what this is supposed to be.
I took a look at some compost drippings in the microscope that day and boy were they festering. This worm was wiggling like crazy!
Apparently the Babylonian number system was base 60 which is why there's 60 seconds in a minute.
This is what Scarlet Johanssen would look like if she was really hairy.

Ok this is pretty interesting. I did this in a tent in the dark and I really like how it came out! See if you can tell what I was trying to draw. This spawned a whole handful of eyes closed drawings that are some of my favorites on the wall.

leastFavoritesExplanation: There are some other lazy drawings on here, but this is lacking even the slightest glimmer of imagination.

story: This was done in haste and shame. It was one of many nights where I just wanted to go to sleep and was a little upset I didn't have energy or inspiration to do something better.
For this one I went onto a busy street and just wrote down things I heard people say

It occurred to me that I'm sort of like a set of genitals running around with all these appendages that help me move, collect food, see, hear, and get the genitals into the right spot to create more gential sustenance gathering bots. So I guess this is a self portrait.
The story here is pretty self-explanatory

leastFavoritesExplanation: I tried to draw Maeve 8 times and failed all 8 times.

story: Up until this point the sticky note wall looked kind of like Soviet clothing: drab and unimaginative. But when I was visiting my parents I found a 15 year old set of watercolors in the basement and went a little wild with the colors for a month or so.

No one ever gets this comic. Look at it first and then I'll tell you the answer... ... ... ... Don't read this until you've looked... ... ... It's supposed to be Dracula at a matress store. I think it looks more like Elvis which throws people off.
My friend Daniel sent me a photo from out the window of his plane that was really inspiring. It's one of the only paintings where I used the whitespace to enhance the composition.
This is somehow related to our D&D campaign.
This is all painted with blackberry drippings from the Presidio. Ain't that fun? Sam, Emma and I walked through the park and ate a ton of berries that day.
Trisha and I sat near Sea Cliff and painted for a while. I made up this oil tanker and put in the landscape we were seeing.
Please come find me so we can play Super Chexx

Emma, Yugel, and I went to go see this really stinky flower that blooms once every seven years. It actually pretty much looked like this. On our way we found a CD tower with someone's entire mid-aughts collection on there including a mix CD called "I'm sorry, I love you". Well, "I'm sorry" to report to you all that it was a universally terrible mix CD. too much Bow Wow, not enough Anthony Hamilton.

This is some Reading Rainbow propaganda depicting what it looks like diving into a world of good books. I was drawing it outside the library and this guy came over like he was interested in what I was making, but 5 minutes later he was still showing me his abstract paint splatter Instagram page.
This was supposed to be Corbin, but I got embarassed and told people it wasn't Corbin since it looks nothing like him, but this is me owning up to the fact that it is supposed to be Corbin.
Jacob and I tag-teamed this. It looks great!

I did 8 acid-infused drawings this day. The purple watercolors used Puget Sound water. There were a lot of thigns worth writing down. There are other ways to see the world that are outside the lens that our society peers through.
Here's what it felt like the night before boarding the bus to Burning Man.
Deanna and Seth went on a deep sea fishing trip and brought this guy back.
It's Daniel Ellsburg, author of my favorite book of the year The Doomsday Machine: confessions of a nuclear war planner. Someone please read it and we can talk about it.
I bought a circle cutter to make a paper chandellier doo-dad. That never happened, but it got some good use on the sticky note project.

I feel like there isn't a "me" as much as there are a bunch of atoms that take my form for a while. This is trying to show that. From 1993 to 2064 some atoms became me but it's not that I died as much as that the atoms just dissipated.
This and the next one really make me smile. Here's my speculative mock-ups for a Seattle basketball team. I would call them the salmon. I like the alternate jersey on the right best.
This is supposed to represent the Holocaust. It has some Guernica inspiration. I read the book Maus which got me thinking about this.

leastFavoritesExplanation: This sickens me. Every section of the drawing was mediocre or just bad. Sorry, Carly.
This doesn't even come close to looking like Seth.

story: I like these drawings of eclectic, eerie combinations. Very Dali, very Corbin.

I think this dog's name is Louie. I met him and the owner while waiting for a flight and then I went to the other side of the boarding area and started drawing. Then I made eye contact with the owner and realized what I was doing was pretty weird. It's definitely less weird than sketching someone's kid, though.
This is Lago Atitlan, Guatemala

The view from Temple 4, Tikal with the city's name glyph on the bottom left. Visiting Tikal was perhaps my favorite thing I've ever done while traveling, and I'm really glad I have this nice painting to remember it by.

leastFavoritesExplanation: I don't know what this is suposed to be. It just makes me think of all the times when I didn't have the will to ideas to create something.

story: It's cool that drawing without looking gives you something that is definitely not recognizable as a bird or a bridge or a boat but it still has its essential essence somehow. Maybe I'm just reading tea leaves here, but it feels like these chaotic lines do represent the shadow or spirit of what I was imagining.
It seems like all jobs essentially pile a Jenga piece onto this giant art project tower that we all have to help build if we want the fruits of its production.

I went to this talk on veganism with the author of The World Peace Diet this day. So great! We can feed everyone and slow climate change and end crazy-efficient animal suffering engines if we just order differently at restaurants.
Isabel and I went on a magical trail ride in Colorado through a snowy forest this day.
This one is a puzzle. Can you figure out what I drew here?
My dad, Andrea, and I went to a western art museum this day and I copied a striking painting of a hunter on snowshoes tracking an elk.
What it feels like to have tons of entities vie for your attention.
Maybe in the future we'll put all our refuse in one bin and use computer vision to sort it in the central plants.
I was thinking I could make a solar calendar by just marking the solstice sun angles on my floor.
Corbin had a dream that I started a cult and coerced all our college friends to join. Here's how that looked.
Everytime I notice this one I have to add something to it. So far it's just circles.

We're getting super groovy and experimental here. I tied a marker to my guitar's neck (did I mention I play guitar?) and played 1234 by Feist (I'm kind of into underground music so it's ok if you haven't heard the song or seen that iPod Nano commercial) while the marker just dragged over the paper. Genius.
I told my housemates I was moving out on this day.
Title: being thirsty
This is supposed to be the ghost of my mother. I was kind of surprised at how eerie is turned out.
There was a huge gas fire for three hours by our house on this day
